description.plain:
Amethyst Amelia Kelly (b. June 7, 1990), better known by her stage name Iggy Azalea, is an Australian rapper and songwriter signed to Island Records and Roc Nation. After being raised in a small town called Mullumbimby and feeling like an outsider, in 2006, at the age of 16, she moved to the United States to pursue a career in hip hop music, stating that she was drawn to the birthplace of rap, and resided in the Southern part of the country.

Moving from Miami to Houston to Atlanta, Iggy absorbed the Southern-style drawl of her surroundings and released her debut project, a mixtape titled Ignorant Art in September 2011, shortly after relocating to Los Angeles. Iggy commented that she made it “with intent to make people question and redefine old ideals.” The project’s raw electronic sound accentuated her unique style that would become a trademark throughout her career. Prior to the release of the mixtape, she had been sharing several home videos on her YouTube channel as an underground rapper and her debut music video for “Pu$$y” quickly went viral due to its explicit nature. In 2012, Iggy became the first female and the first non-American rapper to be featured on XXL’s annual Freshman Class cover issue.

Iggy then aligned herself with the self-proclaimed “King of the South” T.I., who executive produced her free EP Glory released in July 2012 through his Grand Hustle imprint, which included their popular collaboration “Murda Bizness”. Later that year, she was featured on the Hustle Gang Cypher at the BET Hip Hop Awards. In October 2012, Iggy released her second mixtape TrapGold, produced entirely by Diplo and 1st Down of FKi. In the following year, she was selected as the tour opening act for the likes of Beyoncé and Nas.

Iggy’s debut studio album The New Classic was finally released in April 2014 after she secured significant label deals with Island Def Jam and Mercury Records in the previous year. It topped the US Billboard Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums making her the first non-American female rapper to reach the summit of the chart. The album was promoted by a number of single releases: the acclaimed autobiographical “Work”, “Bounce”, “Change Your Life” and the US Billboard Hot 100 chart-topping single “Fancy”, which made Iggy only the fourth female rapper in the history of that chart to reach number one, claiming the longest-leading reign with seven consecutive weeks. She also went on to achieve three top ten hits simultaneously on the Hot 100 along with her feature on Ariana Grande’s “Problem” and the fifth single from the album, “Black Widow,” later that year. The New Classic garnered Iggy four Grammy Award nominations, among many other awards and accolades. In November 2014, the album was reissued in a repackaged version titled Reclassified featuring five newly recorded songs, including “Beg For It” and “Trouble.”

Iggy has also notably collaborated with various other artists such as Jennifer Lopez, Wiz Khalifa and Britney Spears, having amassed hundred millions of streams. In one of the more unlikely crossover success stories, Iggy became one of the most polarizing figures in the music industry suffering a tirade of social media backlash over race and hip-hop culture, but the lightning rod rapper credits the many that have supported her instead, naming some of the women she grew up idolizing particularly Missy Elliott and Lil' Kim.

Digital Distortion had been announced as her sophomore project in 2016 but was ultimately scrapped due to label issues. It was slated to include the singles “Team”, “Mo Bounce”, and “Switch”. In late 2017, Iggy revealed she had parted ways with Def Jam Recordings. She joined Island Records in the following year by releasing the single “Savior.” Her first full project in four years titled Survive The Summer was preceded by the single “Kream” and was finally released on August 3rd, 2018.

Months after the EP Iggy decided to part ways with her label and be independent. In 2019 she released three singles under her own label Bad Dream Records, the songs “Sally Walker,” “Started,” and “Fuck It Up' (with Kash Doll). The tracks are part of her first full project in five years, her sophomore studio album In My Defense that was released on July 19, 2019.

Soon after that her EP Wicked Lips was released after a short delay due to her being five months pregnant at the time, spawning the lead single “Lola”. In 2020 after releasing the Tinashe assisted “Dance Like Nobody’s Watching” Iggy Azalea announced her third official studio album titled End Of An Era released on August 13, 2021, the deluxe version of it on September 17th 2021. The project’s first official single “Sip It” was released on April 2, 2021 along with the B-side “Brazil”. The second official single of the project “I Am The Strip Club” was released on July 2, 2021.

description.plain:
“Work” was Iggy Azalea’s debut single as a lead artist and the first off her debut album The New Classic. Hailed by Iggy as her most personal song, the song was developed with motivational and inspirational intentions to portray her life story; specifically dealing with her struggle as an up-and-coming rapper, and her relocation from her small town of Mullumbimby in Australia to Miami at age 16. In sequence with its lyrical story, the snap and trap track begins with a sad-stringed verse segment before significantly increasing in tempo at its drum and synth-heavy refrain.



The song received acclaim from music critics, with some considering it to be among Azalea’s best output, namely praising her flow and the depth of the lyrical content. Commercially, “Work” became a sleeper hit; going Platinum in the United States, and receiving sales certifications in other countries – and Iggy’s breakthrough into mainstream success.

https://twitter.com/IGGYAZALEA/status/296096830037573632

I came to Miami [from Australia] when I was sixteen. July 4th 2006 is when I moved. I thought that line just said it all… I have never really written a song about my life because I think sometimes when you do something so major, you don’t know how to exactly put it in a song.
- Iggy Azalea



Its music video, directed by Jonas & François, was inspired by several films, including The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert (1994), Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas (1998) and Death Proof (2007). It also received praise from critics and was nominated for the MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist at the 2013 ceremony.

“Kream” is the first official single off of Iggy’s sophomore EP Survive The Summer released on July 6, 2018 via Island Records along with “Tokyo Snow Trip” upon the pre-order of the EP.

The song produced by GT, Wallis Lane & Ronny J features American rapper Tyga. The title is an acronym, with K.R.E.A.M. referencing the 1993 Wu-Tang Clan song C.R.E.A.M. meaning Cash Rules Everything Around Me.

She first teased the single on June 23, 2018 when she posted a snippet on her IG. The official music video directed by Colin Tilley premiered on YouTube on July 6, 2018.

description.plain:
“Sally Walker” is the first single off of Iggy Azalea’s sophomore studio album, In My Defense. The track marks Iggy’s first independent release through her personal label Bad Dreams, and her recently signed EMPIRE partnership deal. The song was first teased on an Instagram post on December 11, 2018, and the song officially dropped a few months later on March 15, 2019.

The song was produced by J. White Did It and is a twerking anthem, which contrasts with the origins of “Little Sally Walker,” a children’s nursery rhyme.

The music video was directed by Colin Tilley and premiered the same day the song was released. In the outro of the video, fans can hear a snippet of another track from the album, titled “Started.”

songs.title: Started

description.plain:
“Started” is the second single off of Iggy Azalea’s sophomore studio album In My Defense released on May 3rd, 2019. The song was written by her and produced by J. White Did It.

On January 24, 2019 Iggy expressed her desire to put a snippet of another song at the end of the video for her first In My Defense single “Sally Walker”. Something very popular in R&B/Hip-Hop music videos in the early 2000s.



 When the video was finally released she revealed that the song in the outro is “Started.”



Borrowing inspiration from Drake’s 2013 single “Started From The Bottom” Iggy is letting people know that she is proud of her struggles that led her to fame. From her humble background in Australia to moving to America when she was 15 to pursue a career in Rap Iggy has every right to brag about her come up and success.

The music video for the song directed by Colin Tilley was released on the same day.

description.plain:
Iggy Azalea’s name first started blowing up after this courageously nasty hit about cunnilingus went viral.

The music video dropped online before the producers completed editing the final version, seven weeks after the shoot took place in the Rollin 60’s Neighborhood Crips in Los Angeles, because, just like any other master mind rap artist would do (she mentions 2Pac specifically), Iggy leaked the video herself in August 2011. Long life friend Shawna Peezy (also at times known as Peezus Christ or just Peezy), intros the video with her explaining the decision, here.
The video was forced off Azalea’s Youtube channel temporarily due to it being premiered without permission from the video’s producers back then.



(The ending of the video and a few parts of the song are from a Youtube video called “Kittens Inspired by Kittens” where a little girl voices over pages from a book about, yeah, well, you guessed it. The intro also contains a dialogue between Eddie Murphy and Grace Jones from their 1992 comedy film Boomerang.)



Iggy’s uncanny and cutthroat lyrics showed the hip-hop community that she was setting herself apart from other female rap artists. This caught the attention of many record labels, after she self-released her debut project, Ignorant Art, the mixtape this song features on.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A2GCga7YLCU

“Pu$$y” originated from her remix of Gucci Mane’s 2011 song “Gucci Two Times” called “Pussy Two Times”.

Iggy explained, “I really liked the song (Pussy 2x), but it was a remix thing. I wanted to make like a part two, I wanted to do it again, bigger and better, have a real video and so that’s why I decided to do that, it was kind of an ongoing experiment.”



The producers' final version of the video was released later in 2011 with additional post-production and does not include the intro of Azalea and her friend, the Boomerang dialogue in the opening scene nor the “Kittens inspired by kittens” sample. It was also later removed from their channel.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RavVOAA45M4

During an interview in 2013, Iggy also revealed the video was based on the 1995 American film Friday:

“[That movie] made me do ‘Pu$$y.’ … The ice cream truck, the cereal, all that … just being on the porch, just the fact that Friday kind of happened just on a neighborhood, and I wanted to do with that video something that is interesting but nothing really happens, and you’re at the front of a house and what could go on as you pass by, and that was from Friday.”

“Savior” is a buzz single, by Iggy Azalea officially released on February 2, 2018, via Island Records along with a lyric video directed by Thom Kerr.

It features Migos rapper Quavo and is produced by Manhun Glow and Cirkut. The song was originally destined to appear on her scrapped sophomore studio album Digital Distortion.

It’s demo version, featuring vocals from producer Verse Simmonds on the hook, leaked online on December 5, 2016. Besides the addition of Quavo, the final reworked version of the track features revamped production and instrumentation as well. Iggy posted the first snippet on social media on January 26, 2018.

https://twitter.com/IGGYAZALEA/status/956778593006178305

In a 2018 Billboard interview, Iggy touched upon the origins of “Savior" saying that Quavo was the one who reached out to her. She expressed how grateful she was during a time when most of the industry has shunned her:

He gains nothing for being on the song…Everybody’s probably just like, ‘Oh, but she sucks,’ or ‘Oh, he just did it for money.’ No, he hit me up and we sent music back and forth, and he wanted to do that song.

description.plain:
The second U.K. single taken off Iggy Azalea’s debut album The New Classic, produced by Reeva & Black. The track was not released in North America until the album’s release.

Iggy said that she initially felt that it was a risky choice for a single, and consulted Nas regarding the decision:

“With ‘Bounce,’ I was like, ‘It’s a pop record. I don’t know.’ [Nas] was like, ‘Just fucking do it. It’s something different. It’s one song, what’s the big deal?’ I couldn’t believe Nas was telling me to do a hip-pop record.”

She also did not intend to include the song on The New Classic, believing that it strayed too far from the album’s musical and lyrical themes, but her record label convinced her otherwise and it was included as one of the album’s three bonus tracks.

The accompanying music video for “Bounce” was filmed in Mumbai, India.

description.plain:
“Murda Bizness” was Iggy’s first promotional track off her Glory EP. Originally intended as the debut single from her album to be released through Interscope Records, Iggy decided to use some of the material from recording sessions she had in Atlanta with T.I. in early 2012 in another free project for her fans after she opted not to sign with the label and to change the album’s direction sonically.



Two accompanying visuals were released for the track. An in-studio video with T.I. and fellow Hustle Gang-mate Chip:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sx1jsorRVA0

And the official music video directed by Alex/2Tone (who had previously worked with Iggy on “My World” and “Beat Down”) which consisted in a parody on the TV series Toddlers & Tiaras:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RzI9VQUHJkU

songs.full_title: Fuck Love by Iggy Azalea
songs.title: Fuck Love

description.plain:
With the beat-eating vocal style of “Walk The Line” and the upbeat, bounciness of, well, “Bounce”. Fuck Love is the closing track from Australian rapper Iggy Azalea’s debut album The New Classic.

With a simple message and the shortest play-time on the album, “Fuck Love” sees Iggy favouring her independance over reliance on other people. All whilst celebrating her materialsitc ways.

Music like the rest of The New Classic, the song was produced by The Arcade and The Invisible Men who wrote the track with Azalea and Rock City.

“Fuck Love” also makes an apperance in the 2015 comedy film “Sisters”.

songs.full_title: Rolex by Iggy Azalea
songs.title: Rolex

description.plain:
In this song Iggy reflects on a past relationship, without explicitly naming the person she directs her comments to. She uses Rolex watches as a metaphor for the wasted time she spent with him.

Iggy Azalea commented on the discussion of old topics within her new album, stating:

… There’s some songs where you feel like, “do I wanna put this on?” Some stuff has been written so long ago, “do I even wanna remember that?” I kinda kept it all, for the most part, on there ‘cause I think people know that it was a long time in the making and it shows the journey.

http://youtu.be/VN4id0Uw7XY?t=2m13s

The relevancy of that with regard to this song is the fact that the theme seems to touch on her past relationship with A$AP Rocky.

songs.full_title: Walk the Line by Iggy Azalea
songs.title: Walk the Line

description.plain:
In the opening to her long-awaited debut album The New Classic, Iggy Azalea uses the metaphor of walking on a line to reflect on the long journey she’s had to take to get to where she is today.

As the intro to the album, “Walk the Line” serves to set the scene: no longer is Iggy rapping about female genitalia (“Pu$$y”) or making money by any means necessary (“Murda Bizness”); the mixtape days have passed, and Iggy is ready to begin the next chapter of her career.

description.plain:
“Fuck It Up” is the third single off of Iggy Azalea’s sophomore studio album In My Defense.

Produced by J. White Did It and Jazze Pha, the song is an uptempo unapologetic twerk anthem. Iggy posted the first snippet of the song in her Instagram story on January 6, 2019.

Jazze Pha also teased an early solo version of the song on February 18, 2019 while working in the studio with Iggy.

https://twitter.com/FergusonNicko/status/1097467129379512320

The official music video directed by Colin Tilley and inspired by the 1997 American comedy film Romy and Michele’s High School Reunion was released along with the track.

songs.title: Iam The Stripclub

description.plain:
“Iam The Stripclub” is the second official single off of Iggy Azalea’s third upcoming studio album The End Of An Era, released on July 2, 2021.

Produced by frequent collaborator J. White Did It the Rap/House strip club anthem was first teased by Iggy on August 7, 2020 in a series of Instagram stories while working in the studio. She confirmed the title of the track on Twitter the next day.



She officially announced it as a single on May 9, 2021 on Twitter. https://twitter.com/iggyazalea/status/1391314478688473092?s=21 While the single’s cover art was revealed on June 28, 2021.

An official music video featuring the ballroom house dancers House Of Balmain was released along with the track. Iggy shared the first video teaser on her Instagram on June 25, 2021. Continuing the self references to her career the video includes homage to the visuals and aesthetics used in her debut single “Work”.
